E'Woman: Hey David, how are the preparations for the Spring Festival going?\nMan: It''s been stressful. We just found out that the main band we booked had to cancel due to illness.\nWoman: Oh no! The festival is only two weeks away. What are you going to do?\nMan: The student committee had an emergency meeting last night. We decided to hire a local Jazz ensemble instead. They''re not as well known, but they''re highly recommended.\nWoman: That actually sounds nice. It fits the outdoor picnic vibe. Have you sorted out the food vendors?\nMan: Mostly. We secured three food trucks, but the university administration is still reviewing the safety permits for the barbecue grills.\nWoman: Do they usually take this long?\nMan: Yes, there are strict fire safety regulations. If they don''t approve them by Friday, we''ll have to rely on pre-packaged sandwiches instead of hot food.', TRUE);


-- ── PART C: Talks / Lectures ─────────────────────────────────
E'Professor: Good morning, class. Today we''ll be discussing the fascinating evolution of a machine we often take for granted—the bicycle. The first human-powered land vehicle, known as the \"draisine\" or \"dandy horse\", was invented in 1817 by Karl von Drais in Germany. However, unlike modern bicycles, it had no pedals! Riders simply pushed their feet against the ground to move forward, much like a scooter.\n\nIt wasn''t until the 1860s in France that rotary cranks and pedals were attached to the front wheel, creating what became known as the \"velocipede\". Because the frame was made of solid wood and the tires were iron, riding it on cobblestone roads was extremely uncomfortable. This earned the velocipede its popular nickname: the \"boneshaker\".\n\nThe pursuit of higher speeds led to the controversial \"penny-farthing\" in the 1870s, which featured a massive front wheel and a tiny rear wheel. While it was much faster, it was notoriously dangerous, since the rider sat high off the ground and could easily tumble over the handlebars over the slightest bump.\n\nFinally, in 1885, the \"safety bicycle\" was introduced. It featured two wheels of equal size and a chain drive connecting the pedals to the rear wheel. Combined with the invention of the pneumatic rubber tire a few years later, the safety bicycle provided a comfortable, stable ride. Its basic design is the blueprint for almost every bicycle we ride today.', TRUE);

